AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background: AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help. Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank. Key Questions:

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers? Data Description:

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Steps to follow:

  1. Perform univariate analysis on the data to better understand the variables at your disposal and to get an idea about the no of clusters. Perform EDA, create visualizations to explore data. (10 marks)
  2. Properly comment on the codes, provide explanations of the steps taken in the notebook and conclude your insights from the graphs. (5 marks)
  3. Execute K-means clustering use elbow plot and analyse clusters using boxplot (10 marks)
  4. Execute hierarchical clustering (with different linkages) with the help of dendrogram and cophenetic coeff. Analyse clusters formed using boxplot (15 marks)
  5. Calculateaveragesilhouettescoreforbothmethods.(5marks)
  6. Compare K-means clusters with Hierarchical clusters. (5 marks)
  7. Analysis the clusters formed, tell us how is one cluster different from another and answer all the key questions. (10 marks)

Execute K-means clustering use elbow plot and analyse clusters using boxplot¶

In [18]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(creditScaledK)
    prediction=model.predict(creditScaledK)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(creditScaledK, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / creditScaledK.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[18]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

# cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
# closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering

Z_avg = linkage(creditScaled_H, metric='euclidean', method='average')
c_avg, coph_dists = cophenet(Z_avg , pdist(creditScaled_H))

Calculate average silhouette score for both methods¶

In [41]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
In [42]:
clusters=range(2,10)
meanSC=[]
creditAttr=ccc_df.iloc[:,2:]
creditScaled=creditAttr.apply(zscore)

#The following loop calculate the silouette score for K-means clustering ...
#           with different number of clusters
for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(creditScaled)
    prediction=model.predict(creditScaled)
    SC=silhouette_score(creditScaled, prediction)
    print('Silhouette Score(n=',k,'):', SC)

from collections import defaultdict 
#This paragraph of code is to compare the difference of two clustering methods 
idSize = comp_df.shape[0]
groupOne = comp_df['K_means_result'].tolist()
groupTwo = comp_df['Hierarchical_result'].tolist()

distanceMatrixOne = defaultdict(dict)
distanceMatrixTwo = defaultdict(dict)
for i in range(idSize):
    for j in range(i+1, idSize):
        if groupOne[i] == groupOne[j]:
            distanceMatrixOne[i][j] = 0
        else:
            distanceMatrixOne[i][j] = 1
        if groupTwo[i] == groupTwo[j]:
            distanceMatrixTwo[i][j] = 0
        else:
            distanceMatrixTwo[i][j] = 1
            
sumDiff = 0
for i in range(idSize):
    for j in range(i+1, idSize):
        if distanceMatrixOne[i][j] != distanceMatrixTwo[i][j]:
            sumDiff += 1
print(sumDiff)

import operator as op
from functools import reduce

def ncr(n, r):
    r = min(r, n-r)
    numer = reduce(op.mul, range(n, n-r, -1), 1)
    denom = reduce(op.mul, range(1, r+1), 1)
    return numer // denom  # or / in Python 2
ratio=sumDiff/ncr(idSize,2)#This give the ratio of different 
print("The ratio of different clustering of the two methods are: ",ratio)
#This gives the cluster difference of two methods when n_clusters = 5

def ClusterIndicesNumpy(clustNum, labels_array): #numpy 
    return np.where(labels_array == clustNum)[0]

def ClusterIndicesComp(clustNum, labels_array): #list comprehension
    return np.array([i for i, x in enumerate(labels_array) if x == clustNum])

The two clustering methods would group the customers into three identical (or extremely similar) clusters, of course with a different cluster label. Because when you run K-means clustering, the label key (0,1,2) is randomly assigned and would change each time you rerun the model.

We can have the following analysis based on the table above:

The group of customers with very high average credit limit (also the most credit cards) and a lot of online logins but very few onsite bank vist is in one group;

The customers with the lowest average credit limit would have the least credit cards and the most calls, totals visits, both online and onsite, lie in middle;

The other group of customers have the the credit limit and number of credit cards in between, this group of customers have the least online visit, intermediate onsite visist and number of calls in the middle.

It is immaginable that customers with the lowest credit limit would need to call the bank more often to resolve issue with their credit or more complaints. The group of customers with the most credit limits and credit cards would need to spend more time to take care of their accounts therefore more online visits. This would leave them less need to go to the bank physically.

I would focus on the group with lowest credit limit and least credit cards to offer them banker appointments or call backs to take care of their issues that they have to called in. Offer them new credit card with higher credit limit might be an option, given good credit score.

I would also offer the group with highest credit limit onsite appointments to explore other business. This group has the least number of customers therefore is more feasible to do that. These customers made the least onsite visits to the bank so an appointment offering might attract them.

I would offer the group with the middle credit limit and the least online visits some online resources and maybe more guidance. It could be the group of elder people that are not familiar with online operation. They have enough credit limit and credit cards but just could not make the best use of online resources due to habits or generational gap.

Conclusion:¶

The difference between the three groups/clusters are very distinctive and give us a lot of insights. We can obtain a lot of insights from the clustering models.
